description: This snail is actually just outside the published measurement range for Helminthoglypta phlyctaena, and just inside the range for Helminthoglypta fieldi, but since it is from oak woodland and not from the the coastal strand habitat of fieldi, it seems more appropriate to list it under phlyctaena.  Perhaps it should be considered an intergrade?  Pilsbry gives the range of height to diameter of fieldi as .74-.82. I measured a sample of 10 shells from the Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History and came to a similar .70-.81. This snails measurements came to .74. The very closely related H. phlyctaena ratio is .60-.66 according to Pilsbry, and 8 shells at the museum came to .63 - .75.  So, fieldi is a little more globose, and phlyctaena a little flatter, but I suspect a large sample would show an overlap like my small sample did.  These two species were originally described as subspeces of H. traskii, and Pilsbry said fieldi is the coastal form and phlyctaena is the inland form. This snail was only 1 km from the coast, in a narrow strip of oaks and willows surrounded by coastal sage scrub.
name: Helminthoglypta phlyctaena
